Current paper introduction: 
The ABO$_3$ perovskite crystal structure is a cornerstone of modern materials science, hosting a remarkable diversity of functional properties that are critical for applications ranging from photovoltaics and catalysis to solid-state electronics. The vast compositional space available by varying the A and B-site cations offers a fertile ground for discovering novel materials with tailored functionalities. High-throughput computational screening, powered by first-principles calculations, has emerged as an indispensable tool for navigating this expansive chemical landscape, enabling the rapid evaluation and prioritization of promising candidate materials. This data-driven paradigm accelerates the materials discovery cycle, bridging the gap between theoretical prediction and experimental synthesis.

A significant bottleneck in high-throughput workflows, however, is the reliability and completeness of the generated data. While thermodynamic stability, often assessed by the energy above the convex hull, is a well-established and robustly computed metric, mechanical properties present a far greater challenge. Datasets of calculated elastic constants are frequently sparse and plagued by physically unrealistic entries, such as negative bulk or shear moduli, which signify structural instability. These artifacts can arise from calculations performed on dynamically unstable structures or from numerical convergence issues. Attempting to train standard regression models on such flawed data to predict mechanical properties is problematic, as the models are easily biased by extreme outliers and unphysical values, leading to poor predictive performance and unreliable materials screening.

To overcome this critical challenge, we introduce a two-stage classification pipeline that circumvents the pitfalls of direct regression on noisy elastic data. Our approach reframes the problem of identifying mechanically robust materials from one of quantitative prediction to one of qualitative assessment. The methodology first filters candidate materials through a classifier trained to predict thermodynamic stability, ensuring that only compounds likely to be synthesizable are considered. Subsequently, instead of attempting to predict the exact values of elastic moduli, a second, dedicated classifier distinguishes between mechanically viable and unstable structures. This mechanical viability model is trained exclusively on a physically vetted subset of the data, learning to recognize the structural and chemical features associated with mechanical robustness without being corrupted by nonsensical data points.

By integrating these sequential classifiers into a multi-objective optimization framework, we screen a large space of uncharacterized ABO$_3$ compounds to identify candidates that simultaneously satisfy the criteria for both thermodynamic stability and mechanical robustness. To further enhance the reliability of our search, we explicitly incorporate model uncertainty, penalizing candidates for which predictions are not confident. This integrated strategy allows us to efficiently navigate the complex trade-offs between competing material properties and isolate a Pareto front of novel, high-confidence perovskite candidates. Our work demonstrates that a classification-first approach provides a powerful and robust strategy for materials discovery, particularly when navigating the imperfect and often unreliable datasets characteristic of high-throughput computation.

